Auto Loan Default Analysis¶

  I will be exploring an auto loan dataset to mine for any significant insights, gather performance indicators, and make a logistic regression model to help classify future auto loans as potential defaults.

  I will be loading packages to help with datamining and to plot data.

  There are some states that have a lot of one or the other in terms of employment type. I will be using state_id to impute some values into employment_type. If one of the options is twice as likely as the other, 2.0 for salaried and 0.5 for self_emplyed, then I will replace the null value.

In [12]:
sa_replaced = [2,14,19,20] #state id's where nulls will become Salaried
se_replaced = [3,7,12,13] #state id's where nulls will become Self employed

for i in sa_replaced + se_replaced: #for loop where I iterate over all necessary state_ids and assign a value to nulls 
    if i in sa_replaced: # two boolean masks being combined: checking for null values and checking for the state_id
        auto.loc[(auto['employment_type'].isnull() & (auto['state_id']==i)),'employment_type'] = 'Salaried'
    else:
        auto.loc[(auto['employment_type'].isnull() & (auto['state_id']==i)),'employment_type'] = 'Self employed'

  As far as the target variable, loan_default, is concerned, about 21.7% of all auto loans are defaulted on. I would like to see if the percent of defaulters changes within different categories such as state_id, branch_id, etc.

Loan Defaults with Respect to Categorical Variables¶

  I want to see the effect of different categorical variables on loan defaults. To accomplish this I need to make a function to give a pivot table with the mean loan_default value, or the default rate, for any category. As well as show the distribution with a bar plot where the categories are ordered from highest to lowest default rate.

In [19]:
def pivot_and_chart(column_name): #making a function to give a bar plot and pivot table for loan_default and the desired category
    
    pivot = pd.pivot_table(auto,values = 'loan_default',index = column_name,aggfunc = np.mean)  #averaging loan default across
                                                                                                #the category
    
    categories = pivot.index #getting the categories for the column
    loan_default_averages = pivot.iloc[:,0] #getting the loan default average for each category
    ordered_categories_desc = pivot.iloc[:,0].sort_values(ascending=False).index #ordering the categories in desc order
                                                                                            #by loan default average
    
    sns.barplot(categories,loan_default_averages,order=ordered_categories_desc,palette = sns.color_palette()) #bar plot of loan default
                                                                                                              #averages by category
    
    len_cat =pivot.shape[0] #getting the length of the horizontal line
    plt.hlines(auto.loan_default.mean(),xmin=-1,xmax=len_cat,label='average loan default') #average loan default line plotted
    
    plt.ylabel('Loan Default Rate')
    plt.title('Loan Defualt Rate w.r.t. {}'.format(column_name))
    plt.show()
    return pivot.sort_values(by='loan_default',ascending = False)
#############binomial test of significance for each category if neeeded def binom_test_auto(column_name): dict_o_cdfs = {} value_counts_defaulted = auto.loc[auto.loan_default==1,column_name].value_counts() value_counts_all = auto[column_name].value_counts() for i in auto[column_name].value_counts().index: if i in value_counts_defaulted.index: k = value_counts_defaulted[i] else: k = 0 n = value_counts_all[i] dict_o_cdfs[i] = binom.cdf(k,n,auto.loan_default.mean()) return pd.Series(dict_o_cdfs) state_binom = binom_test_auto('state_id')

Primary Details¶

  I want to see how the primary account details differ between defaulters and nondefaulters. To do this, I will be plotting the distribution of each primary account detail for defaulters and nondefaulters. I would also like to see how the means and standard deviation differ between defaulters and nondefaulters.

In [45]:
def account_info(i,pri_or_sec): #nothing is returned, it only displays things
    
    ####Function History
    #This was a for loop first, but I turned it into a function instead. That's why it might look weird or inefficient.
    #Some of this code looks like it is only for the primary account, but it works for secondary as well.
    #I just don't want to have to go thru and rename a bunch of stuff. I can also make it more efficient by
    #focusing on a single column from the start, but again, I'd rather not at this time.
    
    ####Variable Description
    #i can only be between 0 and 6.
    #pri_or_sec can take more than pri or sec, but that is what I made the function for
    
    #getting the correct columns with pri_or_sec
    primary_account_cols = pd.Series(auto.columns).str.contains(pri_or_sec) #boolean mask for the primary account detail columns
    primary_account_info = auto.loc[:,list(primary_account_cols)] #primary account columns only dataframe
    
    #describe() information
    new_df = pd.concat([pd.DataFrame(primary_account_info.describe().iloc[1:,i]), #getting the describe() output for each primary account column
              primary_account_info.loc[auto.loan_default==0].describe().iloc[1:,i], #getting the describe() output for each primary account column for defaulters
              primary_account_info.loc[auto.loan_default==1].describe().iloc[1:,i]],axis=1) #getting the describe() output for each primary account column for nondefaulters
    #putting all the above information into one dataframe
    new_df.columns = [pd.DataFrame(primary_account_info.describe().iloc[1:,i]).columns[0]+'_all', #changing column names
                     pd.DataFrame(primary_account_info.describe().iloc[1:,i]).columns[0]+'_nondefaulter',
                     pd.DataFrame(primary_account_info.describe().iloc[1:,i]).columns[0]+'_defaulter']
    display(new_df)
    
    #boxplot
    sns.boxplot(x= 'loan_default', y = primary_account_info.columns[i],data =auto.loc[auto[primary_account_info.columns[i]]!=0])
    if auto[primary_account_info.columns[i]].loc[auto[primary_account_info.columns[i]]!=0].mean()>10:
        plt.yscale('log') #switching to log scale for those columns that need it
    plt.title('Loan Default vs {}'.format(primary_account_info.columns[i]))
    plt.show()
    
    #kdeplot
    fig = sns.kdeplot(auto[primary_account_info.columns[i]].loc[auto.loan_default==0].loc[auto[primary_account_info.columns[i]]!=0],label='nondefaulters')
    fig = sns.kdeplot(auto[primary_account_info.columns[i]].loc[auto.loan_default==1].loc[auto[primary_account_info.columns[i]]!=0],label='defaulters')
    plt.grid(True,axis='y') #putting in horizontal gridlines
    plt.legend()
    if auto[primary_account_info.columns[i]].loc[auto[primary_account_info.columns[i]]!=0].mean()>10:
        plt.xscale('log') #switching to log scale for those columns that need it
    plt.title('Loan Default vs {}'.format(primary_account_info.columns[i]))
    plt.show()

  For all these variables, the majority of observations are 0. I wanted to see the distributions without them.

Logistic Regression Model¶

  I will be splitting my dataset into a train set,75%, and test set, 25%. From there, I will make the model and check its accuracy.

  The model showed that all the loans in the test set would not default. This gave an accuracy of 78.24% with 44917 true negatives, 12488 false negatives, and 0 true positives and false positives. This model is ok and seems to be similar to the one the bank already uses to determine if a borrower should get a loan or not.

  There were 12 variables that were considereded insignificant. The one column that surprises me in this significance test is the voterid_flag since it was seen that they had a percievably larger loan default rate than the other forms of identification.
